#[cfg(test)] //at top of tests to leave out of compiled code
#[test] //to mark a test
#[should_panic] //to mark a test that should panic
cargo test //to run tests note can mark to ignore with #[ignore]
Can place #[cfg(test)] in file with a "mod tests" module
Must add "use super::greet;" to call local functions.

Like Anonymous or Lambda Function... i.e. UnNamed
Isolate variables local to code block (can still see vars outside)
Can still set mutable variables inside code block.
Shadowing... use "let" inside code block to shadow the outside "y" variable
code block begins and ends borrowing of "a" by "b"
same variable name can be reinitialized to any type.
1) Each value in Rust has a variable that’s called its owner.
2) There can only be one owner at a time.
3) When the owner goes out of scope, the value will be dropped.
INTEGER: y makes a COPY of x data... NOT a pointer.
This applies to all "Copy" types... integer, float, char, bool, tuples of Copy type
A compile time Error... IF "s1" is ever referenced again.
String puts (ptr, len, capacity) on stack
s1 Falls out of scope as soon as reference is MOVED from s1 to s2
NOTE: This applies to all variables of type "Move"... i.e. the reference is MOVED from s1 to s2.
Arrays are copied... do NOT move ownership
Ownership is MOVED... vec2 no longer accessible.
To make a deepcopy of String (or other ptr/heap variable)
Shallow copies don't require clone()... e.g. y = x for integer, float, char, bool, etc.
Tuples with only Copy types are also Copy type (i.e. only int, float, char, bool, etc.)
Similar to assigning value to variable.
Function call will either MOVE or COPY just like an assignment.
Functions that return String give ownership to calling assignment
NOTE: s2 is dropped when "let s3 = takes_and_gives_back(s2);" is called.
NOTE: References will make this easier.
NOTE: References will make this easier.
Refer to Value WITHOUT taking ownership... use & Ampersand
NOTE: the borrowed value CAN NOT be modified.
Passing mutable referenct to mutable variable retains ownership with original variable.
Need to use std::any::type_name OR an external crate "typename"
Can get value at pointer location and (if mutable) modify it.
In 2017, code block was required to drop xr and have x retain ownership
NOTE: Still... try to ONLY have one mutable reference to a value.

MUST be String NOT str (size must be known at compile time)

let ts = TStructName ( 10, 20, 30 ); // Again note parens
NOTE: dot access with index... e.g. ts.2
Can be made mutable with: let mut ts = TStructName( val0, val1, ... )
